<br>
I don't know why, but the story really saddened (is that a word?) me, as I watch another hero fall. I grew up thinking that Michael Jordan was the best because not only was he a superstar basketball player, but was also a stand up citizen who gave back to his community and was just a hard working moral decent guy.<br>
<br>
They told stories this morning about how he claims that his wife is nothing more than Hired help who he married to boost his image, how he got this woman pregnant and didn't come through with the money, and who slept with countless women, boozing it up and gambling, etc etc. <br>
<br>
And another hero falls.<br>
<br>
People say that one of the problems of our generation is that we don't have any heroes. No one to look up to any more. My parents had great men and women like Martian Luther King, Jr, JFK (Who we have since found was't that great of a guy), and Jackie O. We have.. spiderman. And, since 9/11.. people can count Police Officers, Fire Fighters, and other public saftey workers amongst heroes. <br>
<br>
I don't know.. I'm just doing a lot of thinking this morning, and was wondering what you all thought about this subject. Is the day of the Hero over? Has the media become so profiecient as to show that every hero is nothing more than a person with big flaws, sometimes much greater than ourselves? Is that why we now look to the honest, hard working men and women of public service instead of the multi-millionares who all seem to live horrible lives of sin. <br>
<br>
I know this is going to mark me as a paraiah, but I actually liked watching this show this summer entitled American Idol. And one of the best things about it was this sweet, honest girl from Texas won the competition. She was so meek and caring, but when she got behind a microphone BAM God could she sing. Her soul poured forth enough to bring tears to people's eyes. And it made me happy that someone so nice and deserving won the contest. She, I thought, is really someone I want to be an Icon for the younger generation of today.<br>
<br>
But now.. I fear she will be absorbed into the life of 'hollywood'.<br>
<br>
I guess I'm rambling, but what do you all think? Have heroes gone to the wayside? Are they necessary? And, more importantly.. are they possible?<br>
<br>
Kuladen <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=serinityoffv>Serinity of FV</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_lightning.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Leviathan Paladin</span><br>  Posts: 122<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(11/20/02 8:41 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm57.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=195.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Heroes</span><hr size=1> My opinion, as society progresses (though some would argue otherwise), our morals are challenged more. Everything we believe in is challenged more than was the norm. We still have these old fashioned ideas of what heros should be, but in today's society, are these ideas really attainable? Everyone needs someone &quot;good&quot; to look up to, but that doesn't have to be someone famous. I would rather it be someone close to the person. Someone the person can actually get a chance to know. Instead of knowing only what the media flings at them, and having those views shattered when the media shows them for what they really are, humans. We all have flaws, big and little, but that doesn't mean You (the generic you), can't be a hero for someone else. <br>
